caption: A few years ago I received a DM from @zohrankmamdani. Only recently did I discover its existence. It was a very unusual DM‚Äîespecially coming from a local assemblyman who would soon be running for higher office. He had very little name recognition at the time, and could have benefited from publicity. But unlike the thousands of messages I‚Äôve received from people with something to promote, Zohran did not ask to be featured on Humans of New York. Instead he asked if he could introduce me to taxi drivers that were struggling beneath the burden of debt. Coming from a man with political ambitions, this self-denying request was so strange as to be almost singular. I don‚Äôt endorse politicians on Humans of New York. But I‚Äôll endorse a good man. And it was a good man who cleared 30 minutes from his schedule yesterday to swing by Grand Central to visit Dear New York. Nearly fifty student artists were visiting that day with their families, and I thought a surprise visit from this widely-loved future mayor would be a special memory for all of them. Before Zohran‚Äôs arrival I was convinced I‚Äôd made a terrible mistake. The Vanderbilt Hall exhibit was filled to capacity with adult visitors. Dear New York is self-funded so there was very little staff and security for crowd control. In the crush of people I was almost certain this special day for the kids would devolve into thirty minutes of selfie requests. But everyone rose to the occasion. Hundreds of adults quickly cleared the room and stood outside the exhibit. Eleven very notable adult artists are also featured in the exhibition, but even they took a step back, so that these students could briefly have the stage to themselves. Each child stood by their work and Zohran was able to meet all of them, one at a time, and honor their contributions to the most-visited art show in New York City. Thanks to everyone who ceded the stage yesterday to make this moment possible. Thank you Zohran for literally sitting down on the floor so that these young artists could feel so tall. Thank you for continually centering other people in your life and work. And thank you, for being such an important part of Dear New York.

caption: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm 66 now. I‚Äôm looking at the end of this journey and I don‚Äôt have time for bullshit. We are mission-specific here, no fluff. The life expectancy for kids in this community is a decade less than my own kids‚Äô. And it‚Äôs a very unhealthy, medically-induced life. It‚Äôs a function of the environment; in this neighborhood there are twenty-nine pharmacies, fifty-five fast food restaurants, and not a single supermarket. But environment can be changed. I started Harlem Grown fourteen years ago by turning an abandoned junkyard into an urban farm‚Äî just to give kids a safe space and teach them about nutrition. But things started happening on the periphery: the kids‚Äô parents would come hang out, and sometimes I‚Äôd send them home with fresh food from the farm: a few herbs, some tomatoes. I thought it was cute at first, but people heard we were giving out food and started showing up. Since then we‚Äôve just kept ramping up. We have fourteen farms now. We‚Äôve tried to stay true to our niche of providing fresh, nutritious, healthy foods: fruits and vegetables in particular. With the help of our partners, last year we were able to give away 160,000 pounds of food. I can regurgitate this shit, but when we get to the personal points man, it just fucks me up. Twenty-three kids from our program became the first in their family to attend four-year colleges. The first girl who ever joined our program is pursuing her PhD. Where would she be without that intervention? That‚Äôs my terror. Imagine if we weren‚Äôt here, how worse it would be for so many. When I started this, I was just looking for a volunteer opportunity. In my mind I was killing time while figuring out my next move. But the kids became my next move. You meet these kids, and you learn about their lives, and what are you supposed to do? When you don‚Äôt know about something‚Äî you can claim you just don‚Äôt know. But once you do know, what do you do? Harlem Grown grew from one tiny, little lot that we called a farm to something that has been able to create so much joy and opportunity. It wasn‚Äôt money that did that. It was time. I had time, and we all have time. But time for what? And that‚Äôs what we have to ask ourselves.‚Äù
